The Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels — For most of the past decade, central banks have made only limited progress in curbing powerful global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has kept interest rates at zero while conducting multiple unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchase operations.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have also followed the Fed's example, each implementing their own versions of so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
But inflation has not risen adequately anywhere.
Although these countries are all fighting deflationary pressures, their monetary policies — and economic performances — are diverging.
The US and the UK now have strong enough growth to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the Eurozone and Japan are ramping up QE, pushing policy long-term interest rates further into negative territory.
What is the reason for this difference?
The short answer is debt.
For decades, the US and the UK have had current account deficits, making them debtor countries, while the Eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses, making them creditor countries.
Negative interest rates benefit debtor countries but harm creditor countries, and thus the negative interest rates introduced after the global economic crisis stimulated recovery in the US and the UK, but had basically no effect on the Eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
So far, most creditor countries in the world — countries with persistent large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland — have experienced negative interest rates, not only on long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also on medium-term bonds.
This is certainly not a good thing.
Despite the limited effectiveness of low interest rates, central banks in these economies continue to adhere to this policy.
If you argue that QE or lowering interest rates cannot bring benefits to the economy, they will deflect the conversation and counter the idea that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — on the surface, this seems impeccable.
But in reality, it is full of flaws.
Basic economics courses mention the peculiar phenomenon of the "backward-bending supply curve of savings": in certain circumstances, lowering interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
Because lower interest rates reduce the income of savers, they will reduce their spending, especially if they have a goal of saving for retirement.
All of this does not negate the general rule — which forms the basis of modern monetary policy — that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other expenditures.
However, the impact varies due to differences in the debt situation of the economies.
In a closed economy, every creditor has a debtor, so whatever the creditors lose due to extremely low interest rates, the debtors should benefit.
But in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors naturally outnumber debtors.
The situation is exactly the opposite for a country with a large amount of foreign debt.
Therefore, the effects of monetary policy with interest rate lower bounds differ between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important because foreign asset positions were often small (measured as a percentage of GDP).
However, today, the foreign asset positions of major industrialized economies are large and increasingly diversified, partly due to the leverage that led to the 2007-2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, at the national level, leverage continues to increase.
Although overall current account imbalances have eased since the beginning of the financial crisis, they have not reversed.
This means that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, diverging from deficit economies.
Some commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, had large current account surpluses when oil prices were high, making them the main exceptions to the divergence in foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, world oil prices have plummeted, reversing the wealth trends in these countries.
Their export earnings have sharply declined — many countries have lost half — forcing them to run deficits, relying on the large sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodity boom.
Now, a significant reduction in spending has become inevitable.
Industrialized economies face completely different challenges.
Their problem — in a way, a luxury problem — is to ensure that consumers spend the windfall gains from the decline in import prices.
But in creditor countries, negative interest rates seem to be failing to advance this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This divergence also exists within the Eurozone.
Although as a whole, the Eurozone is a creditor economy, there are also debtor countries within it.
Debtor economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now frequently run current account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
But the current account surpluses of traditional debtor countries are too high, leading to continued increases in the debtor/creditor country asymmetry.
Most notably, since the outbreak of the financial crisis, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, meaning that the surplus accumulated by Germany during this period has exceeded the total historical surplus prior to this.
Following the current trend, Germany's creditor position could increase from 60% of GDP to 100%.
Central bank governors should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend of central bank independence precisely because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem to lack patience, greatly troubled by low inflation, even though the output gap is gradually closing, and the US and Japan have achieved full employment.
Central bank governors in debtor countries must stop manipulating the economy with more monetary easing that may be detrimental to production.
Instead, they should allow the recovery to develop on its own, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effect of falling oil prices to fade.
European Central Bank Governor Draghi recently acknowledged that the current monetary policy framework may not be effective in today's global environment.
But promising more of the same is not a solution.
